  "footnotes": [
    "Battle of Guadalete (711): the Umayyad general Tariq ibn Ziyad crossed from North Africa with a small force and defeated the Visigothic king Roderic; within three years almost the entire peninsula was under Arab-Berber control — one of the fastest conquests in history; the name 'Gibraltar' derives from Jabal Tariq (Tariq's Mountain)",
    "Umayyad Caliphate of Córdoba (929–1031): Abd al-Rahman III declared himself Caliph in 929, making Córdoba one of the largest and most cultured cities in Europe; its Great Mosque (Mezquita), the library of 400,000 volumes, and its multi-faith intellectual culture represented Islamic civilization's apex in the West",
    "Reconquista: the gradual Christian reconquest was not a unified crusade but a complex political process spanning 780 years (718–1492); Muslim, Christian, and Jewish populations coexisted and intermingled throughout; the fall of Granada in 1492 coincided with Columbus's voyage — both initiated by Queen Isabella",
    "Almoravids and Almohads: both were Berber reform movements from the western Sahara/Atlas who were invited by Andalusian taifa rulers to halt Christian advances; the Almohads destroyed the sophisticated Andalusian culture they came to defend, persecuting Maimonides and Averroes alike",
    "1492 — Spain's pivotal year: three events in one year: conquest of Granada ending 780 years of Reconquista; the Alhambra Decree expelling Jews; Columbus's voyage that began the American Empire; together these define the birth of modern Spain"
  ]
